# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# CLI entry-point `partial` on `main : IO ()`
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Why exempted:
#   The Idris2 standard-library `IO` primitives (`putStrLn`, `getLine`,
#   file-handle ops) are not declared `total` upstream, so a top-level
#   `main : IO ()` that uses them cannot be marked `total` without
#   rewriting the entire IO surface. The escape hatch is confined to
#   the outermost CLI shell, which performs no proof work — every call
#   into the library proper goes through the totality-checked `Proven.*`
#   API. This is the canonical "partial top, total interior" pattern.
#
# Audit invariants for each exempted file:
#   - `partial` appears on the line immediately preceding `main : IO ()`.
#   - The body of `main` calls only `IO` primitives and `Proven.*` exports.
#   - No `believe_me`, no `idris_crash`, no `%unsafe` inside `main`.
#
